    "Q1. How can you create a Bokeh plot using Python code?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "828dc19a-efc4-4148-b851-a1c684d030c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To create a Bokeh plot using Python code, you need to follow these steps:\n",
    "\n",
    "Import the necessary modules and functions from the Bokeh library:\n",
    "python\n",
    "Copy code\n",
    "from bokeh.plotting import figure, show\n",
    "from bokeh.io import output_notebook\n",
    "Prepare the data you want to plot. This can be done by creating lists or NumPy arrays for the x and y coordinates:\n",
    "python\n",
    "Copy code\n",
    "x = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
    "y = [6, 7, 2, 4, 5]\n",
    "Initialize the Bokeh figure object by calling the figure function and specifying the desired plot attributes:\n",
    "python\n",
    "Copy code\n",
    "p = figure(title='My Bokeh Plot', x_axis_label='X-axis', y_axis_label='Y-axis')\n",
    "Add glyphs (markers or lines) to the figure object to represent the data:\n",
    "python\n",
    "Copy code\n",
    "p.circle(x, y, size=10, color='blue', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "Display the plot using the show function:\n",
    "python\n",
    "Copy code\n",
    "show(p)\n",
    "By default, Bokeh plots are displayed in a separate browser tab. However, if you want to display the plot directly in a Jupyter Notebook or JupyterLab, you can call the output_notebook function before calling show:\n",
    "\n",
    "python\n",
    "Copy code\n",
    "output_notebook()\n",
    "This will enable the notebook output for Bokeh plots.\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember to have the Bokeh library installed in your Python environment. You can install it using pip install bokeh."
   ]
  },
